0365141630173, 0.026318730786442757, -0.00939858891069889, -0.012153809890151024, -0.03853287547826767, -0.01671903021633625, -0.028048286214470863, -0.01319288369268179, 0.030220285058021545, -0.006971849128603935, 0.004461313132196665, -0.007166256662458181, -0.04445894435048103, 0.013782809488475323, -0.04853479564189911, -0.004876942373812199, 0.015364882536232471, -0.00858744140714407, -0.029147692024707794, -0.0157402902841568, 5.975721069262363e-05, -0.007581885904073715, -0.0030133137479424477, 0.033572133630514145, 0.015096735209226608, 0.011597403325140476, -0.028504136949777603, -0.02992532216012478, -0.007709256373345852, -0.0022658510133624077, 0.015753697603940964, -0.01173147652298212, 0.014640883542597294, -0.002431767527014017, 0.0013943698722869158, -0.01191247720271349, 0.005295923911035061, 0.007548367604613304, -0.027230434119701385, 0.035985466092824936, -0.00434064632281661]], "input": ["\"PROFIT CENTRE\":\"A profit centre is a business segment where revenues are received and expenditures are incurred.\"", "\"INVESTMENT CENTRE\":\"An investment centre is a profit centre that also has some control over its capital expenditure (investment in assets).\"", "\"TOP-DOWN BUDGETING\":Top-down budgeting involves senior management preparing budgets centrally, often with little to no input from junior managers. In this approach, budgets are prepared by senior management and then imposed on the departments responsible for achieving them.", "\"BOTTOM-UP BUDGETING\":\"Bottom-up budgeting,\" also known as participative budgeting, is a budgeting approach where departments and managers at various levels actively participate in preparing their own budgets. These budgets are then reviewed and adjusted by senior management. This method contrasts with top-down budgeting, where senior management prepares the budget with little to no input from lower-level managers. Understanding the implications of transitioning from a top-down to a bottom-up system of budgeting is crucial for effective financial planning and management.", "\"FACTORS TO CONSIDER IN BUDGET PARTICIPATION\":\"Factors to consider in deciding the level of participation in budgeting include the attitudes and skills of junior managers, interdependence between departments, financial difficulty, local knowledge of senior managers, and organizational culture.\"", "\"PROBLEMS WITH ROLLING BUDGETS\":\"Problems with rolling budgets include the process being more time-consuming and costly due to regular updates, and the potential for budgets to be changed to hide operational inefficiencies.\"", "\"APPROPRIATENESS OF ROLLING BUDGETS\":\"Rolling budgets are more appropriate in dynamic industries where external changes can quickly make the original budget outdated. In stable industries, continuously updating the budget may offer little benefit.\"", "\"QUIZ: ROLLING BUDGETS\":\"This quiz asks whether rolling budgets would be appropriate for organizations in various industries, such as food retailing, mobile device manufacturing, airlines, advertising agencies, and retail banking.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF ROLLING BUDGETS\":\"This example shows how Company A computed a 2-quarter rolling budget for one of its outlets, including adjustments for rental increases, new labor regulations, and cheaper material supplies.\"", "\"QUIZ: ROLLING BUDGETS FOR HOMELAND AIRWAYS\":\"This quiz involves updating Homeland Airways' quarterly budget based on changes in fuel costs, labor costs, and assumptions for the next year's budget.\"", "\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\":Incremental budgeting is a traditional budgeting method where the new budget is prepared using the previous period's budget or actual performance as a base, with incremental amounts added for the new budget period. Adjustments are made for expected changes such as inflation, planned increases in sales prices, and costs. This method is straightforward, easy, and quick to perform, making it suitable for stable environments. However, it can encourage inefficiency, carry forward errors, and may not be suitable for volatile industries due to its less flexible nature.", "\"EXAMPLE OF INCREMENTAL BUDGETING IN A SCHOOL\":\"A school has budgeted $1.5 million for staff salaries this year. When preparing the budget for the next year, the head teacher estimates: two new members of staff will be needed to teach languages, with a salary of $30,000 each (before any pay rises); all staff members will be awarded a pay increase of 5% in line with inflation. The budget for staff will then be $1.638 million [($1.5m + $30k + $30k) * 1.05], an overall increase of 9.2%.\"", "\"USEFULNESS OF INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\":\"Incremental budgeting may be appropriate for a stable business with good cost control. Managers need only justify the increments. The system is relatively simple to operate and easy to understand. Conflicts should be avoided if departments can be seen to be treated similarly. Coordination between budgets is easier to achieve, as increments in functional budgets are easily aggregated into master budgets. The effect of change can be seen quickly.\"", "\"PROBLEMS WITH INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\":\"Incremental budgeting assumes activities and methods of working will continue in the same way regardless of whether they are needed. It gives no incentive for developing new ways of working or the reduction of costs. It encourages a 'spend it or lose' mentality so that the budget is maintained next year. The budget may become out of date and no longer relate to the level of activity or type of work being carried out. The priority for resources may have changed since the budgets were set originally. Any budgetary slack in a previous budget is not reviewed. It is also easier to add and justify budgetary slack to make achieving budgets easier. When a budgeting system has been in operation for some time, there is a tendency for the following year's budget to be justified by referencing the levels currently being achieved. However, the analysis process should consider all changes affecting the organisation's future activities. Even using such an analytical base, some organisations find that historical comparisons, particularly the current resource constraints, can inhibit innovative budget changes. This can severely handicap an organisation because the budget should be the first year of the long-term strategic plan. If changes are not started in the budget period, it will be more difficult for the organisation to make the progress necessary to achieve long-term objectives.\"", "\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING (ZBB)\":Zero-Based Budgeting (ZBB) is a budgeting method where all expenses must be justified for each new period, starting from a 'zero base.' This approach requires the costs and benefits of all activities to be quantified and justified, making it particularly useful in the public sector, although it is costly and time-consuming to implement. ZBB involves developing the budget from an assumption of no existing resources, necessitating that all resources be justified and compared with alternatives.\n\nThe process of ZBB includes three main steps: identifying activities and creating decision packages, ranking these packages by their benefits, and allocating resources based on priority. Managers are required to identify activities, consider different ways of performing them, and describe them in a 'decision package' that analyzes costs, states purposes, and identifies alternative methods. This method forces managers to justify all expenses and consider alternative ways of performing activities, ensuring an efficient allocation of resources. Every function within an organization is analyzed for its needs and costs, promoting a thorough and rational approach to budgeting.", "\"FEATURES OF ZBB\":\"FEATURES OF ZBB\" include focusing on activities or programs, asking critical questions about the necessity and cost of activities, and breaking the budgetary process into three stages: identifying activities, reviewing and ranking decision packages, and allocating resources. Unlike traditional budgets, which are typically produced using a 'line item' approach that lists each type of expense and the amount budgeted by each department, ZBB emphasizes the activities or programs each department would like to undertake. It considers questions such as the necessity and efficiency of each activity."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}